values:
WARNING: EXTREME SPOILERS FOR "All Hell Breaks Loose Pt 2" - read at your own risk:

I almost don't know where to begin. Tonight's episode left me alternating between sitting on the edge of my seat and literally crying out in dismay. It was fantastic - and even more so because they started it out with Kansas' "Carry On Wayward Son." I first became acquainted with this song about this time last year, and it was perfect then, and while not as good of a montage, the song already forever means Supernatural for me, so the perfection continued.

As for the episode itself... the beginning had rooted to my spot. Dean's anguish was so palpable - and everything that I ever thought it would be if the end came to this. Though, on a side note, how lucky we are that when Sam gets killed, he's stabbed in the back which left little mess and gore. But Sam was dead. DEAD. And Dean was all big brother love and mourning. He was self-destructive, in pain, and his journey to the crossroads was a natural progression. And Dean was only given one year? Well, I guess we know what next year's Supernatural running-theme will be focused upon.

But now we come to the downsides, for it was Sam that was brought back, but it also wasn't our Sam. The Sam-girl in me really, really is hating this fact - is rebelling against it. In the entire series, I don't think I've ever really seen Sam take down something that even resembles a human, and in this... he was completely un-Sam. He not only took down Jake, he TOOK DOWN JAKE - and with authority. It was brutal, it was final, and it wasn't Sam.

It wasn't Sam.

This worries me, saddens me, and makes me want to tear out my hair in frustration. How could they change the core components of a beloved character? What's dead should stay dead. Poor Sammy! Poor Dean! I was so angry by this development that the episode was almost ruined for me. And then entered Jeffrey Dean Morgan as John Winchester and my heart soared. I LOVE his character and I kept my fingers crossed that we would be seeing him again. It's unfortunate that this is obviously the last time we will be seeing him. Now I see why we didn't see him in the AU episode - it would have lessened the impact that seeing him here, now, had on the audience.

So I excited, thrilled - only to have everything plummet as Sam once more got the shaft in the daddy department. In the beginning of this season John shows his love for Sam, but he never says goodbye. He gives his goodbye only to Dean, and I always felt awful for Sam for it showed a kind of favoritism that I'm sure must always linger in the back of Sam's head. His dad never said goodbye to him. They never got to make their peace. And then here, in this episode, once more we see that shafting happen. John approaches Dean, puts his hand on Dean, and yes, while he spares Sam a glance and a small nod, even to the very end it's as though he only has eyes for his eldest son.

Poor Sam.

By this point I was really, really feeling down on this episode. Talk about a not very Sam-friendly episode - and one that's bound to forever change the brother dynamic that we so love. But then... then the greatness happened. Everything that I've been feeling frustrated about all season finally saw fruition when in the last few moments while Dean is explaining how it was his job to give his life for Sam because it's his job to protect him... and Sam finally explains that it's not just Dean's job. Sam finally, FINALLY steps up to the plate and verbalizes that not only can he save himself, protect himself, but that he's going to protect Dean as well. It really makes my tag for Pt.1 seem all the more accurate! Go SAM! Maybe there's still hope for everything after all.

Well, here's keeping my fingers crossed, and while no, I don't see myself doing another tag or really joining the fanfiction community in this genre quite yet, I do look forward to seeing where my fellow authors will take this development. Who knows, maybe they'll find redemption where all I see is chaos.

And now let the interminable summer begin.

It really is a strange concept to have what basically amounts to an on-line diary.  I'm generally a private person - my thoughts are my own, and I only share them with my closest of friends.  Then there comes the point of... does anyone really want to know what I think?  It seems as though people are interested in that which I write, and the worlds that I create, and the fictional, and yet much-loved lives that I enjoy ruining.  But that's a fictionalized world, where everything happens on my schedule and according to my will.  That's not RL - not me.

Do words in RL really matter?
